[[Category:Mathematical terminology]]


{{abstract-algebra-stub}}

{{other uses|Property (disambiguation)}}
In [[mathematics]], a property is any characteristic that applies to a given set.<ref>https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/sets-introduction.html Retrieved October 15 2018</ref> Rigorously, a property ''p'' defined for all elements of a set ''X'' is usually defined as a function ''p'': ''X'' →  {true, false}, that is true whenever the property holds; or equivalently, as the subset of ''X'' for which ''p'' holds; i.e. the set {''x''&nbsp;|&nbsp;''p''(''x'')&nbsp;=&nbsp;true}; ''p'' is its [[indicator function]]. However, it may be objected that the rigorous definition defines merely the [[extension (semantics)|extension]] of a property, and says nothing about what causes the property to hold for exactly those values.

Examples of properties include the [[commutative property]] of [[real number|real]] and [[complex number]]s and the [[distributive property]].

